trans-unit.source: Consider the problem of matching a string in parentheses, allowing for unlimited nested parentheses. Without the use of recursion, the best that can be done is to use a pattern that matches up to some fixed depth of nesting. It is not possible to handle an arbitrary nesting depth. Perl 5.6 has provided an experimental facility that allows regular expressions to recurse (among other things). The special item (?R) is provided for the specific case of recursion. This PCRE pattern solves the parentheses problem (assume the PCRE_EXTENDED option is set so that white space is ignored): \( ( (?>[^()]+) | (?R) )* \)

Consider the problem of matching a string in parentheses, allowing for unlimited nested parentheses. Without the use of recursion, the best that can be done is to use a pattern that matches up to some fixed depth of nesting. It is not possible to handle an arbitrary nesting depth. Perl 5.6 has provided an experimental facility that allows regular expressions to recurse (among other things). The special item (?R) is provided for the specific case of recursion. This PCRE pattern solves the parentheses problem (assume the PCRE_EXTENDED option is set so that white space is ignored): \( ( (?>[^()]+) | (?R) )* \)
trans-unit.target: Considere el problema de hacer coincidir una cadena entre paréntesis, lo que permite un número ilimitado de paréntesis anidados. Sin el uso de la recursividad, lo mejor que se puede hacer es usar un patrón que coincida con una profundidad fija de anidación. No es posible manejar una profundidad de anidamiento arbitraria. Perl 5.6 ha proporcionado una función experimental que permite que las expresiones regulares se repitan (entre otras cosas). El elemento especial (? R) se proporciona para el caso específico de recursividad. Este patrón de PCRE resuelve el problema de los paréntesis (suponga que la opción PCRE_EXTENDED está configurada para que se ignore el espacio en blanco): \ (((?> [^ ()] +) | (? R)) * \)
